snippet.textDisplay: There are many points to address on this matter but as a black American woman I have to comment on the “racism” the Duchess of Sussex has faced. I put racism in quotes because nasty headlines is not racism. Racism is when people of power and influence prevent a person or persons from a different ethnic group or color from improving their in place society. I am very troubled that prejudice, of which we are all guilty of in some way, is being conflated with racism. The Duchess of Sussex was not prevented from marrying into the royal family; if she had that would have indeed been racism at work. Nasty headlines and tweets are just that...nasty. Prejudice is part of the human condition; racism, however, at least on my side of the pond, has been legally eradicated. I can vote, own property, attend whatever school I desire, live in any neighborhood I desire , and cannot be denied access to public facilities I help pay taxes on. So, with all due respect to the Scottish journalists on this panel, who is brown like me: The Duchess is not dealing with racism she’s dealing with prejudice from some people who hate themselves. As a black woman, she (and I) will deal with that for the rest of her life. If that is their reason for stepping back that is regrettable. How much more of a powerful example it would have been for them to stay and face it head on as has been the history of blacks in America. Running from prejudice will only embolden it and make those people think they have won.
